Child Page 1: Proposal: Business-Area-Aligned Integration Server Model

Purpose

This page proposes aligning Integration Servers to specific business areas instead of hosting applications from multiple business areas across shared servers.

The objective is to reduce cross-business impact during deployments, improve testability, simplify rollback and support, and create clearer ownership boundaries.

Current State / Problem

At present, applications belonging to different business areas are distributed across multiple Integration Servers, and each Integration Server may host applications from several business domains.

This creates a number of operational and delivery challenges:
	•	A deployment in one area may unintentionally impact another business area
	•	Shared library changes carry wider risk than necessary
	•	Testing is more difficult because unrelated applications coexist on the same servers
	•	Rollback becomes more complicated when multiple business areas are mixed together
	•	Troubleshooting and support ownership are less clear
	•	Resource contention or instability on a shared server can affect unrelated services

This architecture increases the blast radius of technical changes and makes controlled delivery more difficult.

Proposed Change

Move toward a model where Integration Servers are aligned to business areas.

Under this approach:
	•	applications for a given business area are deployed only to Integration Servers allocated to that business area
	•	unrelated business areas do not share the same runtime wherever practical
	•	business-domain isolation becomes a design principle for server allocation

This does not necessarily require one server per application. The proposal is to group applications by business domain, not to maximize infrastructure count unnecessarily.

Benefits

Reduced blast radius

A deployment issue, memory issue, shared component issue, or configuration issue in one business area is less likely to affect another.

Safer testing

Changes can be tested in an environment that reflects the target business domain without interference from unrelated applications.

Easier impact assessment

When evaluating a deployment or incident, the affected scope becomes easier to identify because the runtime is already aligned to one business area.

Simpler rollback

Rollback activity is more controlled because only one business area’s server group is involved.

Better support ownership

Support teams can identify ownership more easily when applications are grouped by business domain.

Improved release flexibility

Business areas can plan and execute releases more independently, without needing to coordinate around mixed server usage.

Better operational stability

An overloaded or unstable server will have a more contained effect, rather than disrupting multiple business areas.

Easier capacity planning

Infrastructure sizing and tuning can be better aligned to the usage profile of a specific business area.

Better long-term architecture

This is a step toward stronger domain separation, lower coupling, and clearer platform structure.

Challenges / Risks

Migration effort

Re-aligning applications to business-area-specific servers will require planning, testing, and phased migration.

Dependency discovery required

Some applications may have dependencies that are not fully documented today, and these will need to be understood before migration.

Potential increase in infrastructure footprint

Depending on the target design, there may be some increase in infrastructure or operational overhead.

Transitional complexity

For some time, both the current mixed model and the new aligned model may need to coexist.

Not every service may be isolated immediately

Some technical or shared services may still need to remain cross-cutting until further design changes are made.

What Needs to Change

The following areas may need to be reviewed or updated:
	•	current application-to-server mapping
	•	target server allocation model by business area
	•	deployment pipeline targets
	•	environment naming and ownership conventions
	•	monitoring and alerting aligned to business domains
	•	support model and escalation ownership
	•	capacity planning approach

Suggested Approach

A phased rollout is recommended rather than a full redesign in one step.

Phase 1

Identify business areas, current application placement, and server-sharing patterns.

Phase 2

Select one business area as a pilot and move it toward a dedicated Integration Server model.

Phase 3

Validate benefits, refine design standards, and document lessons learned.

Phase 4

Gradually extend the model to additional business areas.

Open Questions
	•	Which business area is the best candidate for pilot implementation?
	•	Are there any hard technical dependencies preventing separation?
	•	What is the minimum viable server isolation model we can adopt first?
	•	Are there shared services that should remain central for now?
	•	What operational standards should be defined before migration begins?

Recommendation

Adopt business-area alignment as a target architectural principle and begin with a pilot implementation for one business domain.

