Child Page 2: Proposal: Controlled Application Flow Management During DB / Infrastructure Patching

Purpose

This page proposes a controlled operational process for database patching and other infrastructure changes that may interrupt or destabilize application processing.

The objective is to reduce patch-related production risk by ensuring that application flows are safely stopped before patching begins, or that such work is performed within an agreed maintenance window.

Current State / Problem

Database patching and infrastructure patching may affect application stability, transaction processing, and connectivity.

At present, there is a risk that:
	•	application flows may continue to run while patching is in progress
	•	transactions may fail mid-processing
	•	recovery steps may be inconsistent across teams
	•	patch-related outages may be harder to control and diagnose
	•	the stop/start approach may depend too much on manual judgement

This creates unnecessary risk during maintenance activity, especially where applications are sensitive to database availability or platform changes.

Proposed Change

For any DB patching or infrastructure patching that could affect application processing, one of the following controls should be mandatory:
	•	the activity is performed in a defined maintenance window, or
	•	the change includes a controlled pre-step to stop affected application flows before patching begins

The stop/start process should be standardized and, where feasible, automated through a job or controlled operational task that stops specific applications or flows in a predictable way.

Rather than attempting to solve this across all services immediately, the proposal is to begin with RMI / GMG, define the process and design, and then expand to additional services over time.

Proposed Operating Process

Pre-patch
	•	identify which services or applications are affected
	•	assess whether active flows must be stopped
	•	execute a controlled stop process for the impacted applications
	•	verify that processing has fully quiesced before patching begins

During patching
	•	perform patching only after safe stop is confirmed
	•	monitor technical health and change progress
	•	ensure no unexpected re-triggering of stopped flows

Post-patch
	•	restart applications or flows using a controlled procedure
	•	validate connectivity and technical health
	•	perform application-level checks
	•	confirm normal processing has resumed

Benefits

Reduced risk of in-flight transaction failures

Stopping flows before patching reduces the chance of incomplete or failed processing.

Better operational control

Patch execution becomes more structured and less dependent on ad hoc decisions.

Improved auditability

The change record can show clearly what was stopped, when it was stopped, and how recovery was performed.

Faster and more predictable recovery

A defined restart and validation sequence improves restoration quality.

Lower incident risk

Patch-related outages become easier to prevent and easier to manage.

Reusable model for other services

Starting with RMI / GMG allows the process to be proven and refined before broader rollout.

Challenges / Risks

Additional process overhead

Stopping flows, validating state, and restarting services adds extra steps to the patching process.

Automation effort

Operational jobs or scripts may need to be designed and tested.

Dependency knowledge required

Teams need a clear understanding of service dependencies and stop/start sequencing.

Business availability considerations

If flows are stopped, there may be temporary unavailability that needs to be planned and communicated.

What Needs to Change

The following may need to be updated:
	•	change management templates
	•	patch runbooks
	•	stop/start operational jobs
	•	validation and health-check procedures
	•	support handoff during maintenance activity
	•	dependency documentation
	•	maintenance window decision criteria

Initial Scope

Start with:
	•	RMI
	•	GMG

For these services, define:
	•	what must be stopped before patching
	•	who approves the stop/start process
	•	how safe stop is validated
	•	how restart is performed
	•	which post-patch checks are mandatory

Suggested Approach

Step 1

Document current patching risks and identify where uncontrolled processing could occur.

Step 2

Design a standard stop/start process for RMI / GMG.

Step 3

Test the process in non-production where possible.

Step 4

Use the process in selected controlled changes.

Step 5

Refine and roll out gradually to additional services.

Open Questions
	•	Which patch types should always require flow stoppage?
	•	Which services can be stopped independently, and which need coordinated shutdown?
	•	Can stop/start be fully automated or should it remain semi-manual initially?
	•	What evidence should be required before patching can begin?
	•	What post-patch validation should be mandatory before reopening flows?

Recommendation

Define and pilot a controlled patching process for RMI / GMG, with stop/start controls as part of the change where patching could affect transaction processing.

