Child Page 3: Proposal: Shared Library Decomposition and Ownership Model

Purpose

This page proposes restructuring the current shared library approach to reduce coupling, improve maintainability, and lower the risk of cross-business impact from common component changes.

The objective is to separate truly common technical functionality from exception handling and business-area-specific logic, and to establish clearer ownership of shared components.

Current State / Problem

The current common shared library has grown into a large component containing multiple responsibilities, including:
	•	exception handling
	•	general common utilities
	•	other reusable code
	•	potentially business-area-specific logic

This creates several problems:
	•	a change in the shared library can affect many unrelated applications
	•	regression testing becomes larger and more complex than necessary
	•	ownership is not always clear
	•	business-specific code can become mixed with platform-wide code
	•	release planning becomes harder because too many applications depend on one large component
	•	the common component becomes difficult to understand and maintain over time

The current model increases coupling and makes even small changes carry a wider risk footprint.

Proposed Change

Decompose the current shared library into smaller, well-defined components with clear responsibility boundaries.

The target direction is:
	•	keep only truly common technical utilities in a central shared component
	•	move exception handling into a separate dedicated component
	•	move business-area-specific reusable code into business-area-specific shared libraries
	•	define ownership and contribution rules for each shared component

Target Structure (Illustrative)

Example structure:
	•	common-core
Contains only generic technical utilities used across multiple domains
	•	common-exception-handling
Contains shared exception handling and related framework logic
	•	shared-rmi
Contains reusable logic specific to RMI
	•	shared-gmg
Contains reusable logic specific to GMG

This is an example only, but it illustrates the principle that cross-cutting technical concerns and business-domain-specific reusable code should not be bundled into one oversized shared component.

Benefits

Reduced deployment risk

A change to one business-area-specific shared component is less likely to affect unrelated applications.

Better modularity

Smaller components are easier to understand, test, and maintain.

Clearer ownership

Each shared component can have an identified owning team or business domain.

Easier impact analysis

It becomes easier to identify which applications are affected by a component change.

Better release independence

Business-area-specific changes can be planned and released with less platform-wide coordination.

Lower coupling

Applications depend only on the shared components they actually use.

Better maintainability

Developers and support teams can work with smaller, cleaner modules instead of one large mixed-responsibility library.

Better governance

A defined structure makes it easier to decide where new reusable code should belong.

Challenges / Risks

Refactoring effort

Breaking up the current shared library will require dependency analysis, code movement, testing, and migration planning.

Migration complexity

Existing applications will need to be updated gradually to consume the new component structure.

Versioning considerations

Once components are split, versioning and compatibility need to be managed carefully.

Temporary coexistence

Old and new component structures may coexist during transition, which may add short-term complexity.

Governance must be enforced

Without agreed standards, new code may again accumulate in the wrong place.

What Needs to Change

The following areas may need review:
	•	shared library structure
	•	repository layout
	•	build and dependency management
	•	versioning strategy
	•	ownership model
	•	coding standards for what qualifies as “common”
	•	migration plan for existing consumers
	•	regression and compatibility testing approach

Suggested Design Principles

The following principles are recommended:
	•	enterprise-wide shared libraries should contain only truly common technical logic
	•	cross-cutting technical concerns should be isolated from business logic
	•	business-area-specific reusable code should sit in business-area-specific components
	•	each shared component should have clear ownership
	•	changes to shared components should require impact analysis and appropriate test evidence

Suggested Approach

Phase 1

Analyse the current shared library contents and classify code into:
	•	truly common
	•	exception handling
	•	business-area-specific logic
	•	unclear / mixed ownership

Phase 2

Define target components and ownership.

Phase 3

Extract one or two clearly separable modules first, such as exception handling or one business-specific reusable area.

Phase 4

Migrate applications gradually to the new structure.

Phase 5

Retire the legacy oversized shared library over time, or reduce it to true core functionality only.

Open Questions
	•	Which parts of the current library are truly enterprise-wide?
	•	Which code is actually business-area-specific today?
	•	Should exception handling be fully centralised in its own component?
	•	What ownership model should be assigned to each shared component?
	•	How should versioning and compatibility be controlled during migration?

Recommendation

Begin a structured decomposition of the current shared library, starting with separation of exception handling and identification of business-area-specific logic that should move into domain-owned shared components.

